surviving.recommendation:
Add a pnpm `overrides` entry to package.json forcing the fixed transitive version, then reinstall and re-audit:

  "pnpm": {
    "overrides": {
      "protobufjs": ">=7.5.8"
    }
  }

Then `pnpm install` and `pnpm audit --prod` to confirm the protobufjs critical/high/moderate advisories clear. Do NOT rely on "bump firebase to latest 12.x" alone: the current latest @grpc/proto-loader@0.8.1 still declares `protobufjs ^7.5.5`, which permits 7.5.5 — still vulnerable to the high/moderate advisories (patched >=7.5.6) — so a firebase bump may not fully remediate. The override pins protobufjs to a clean version regardless of the proto-loader range. (Note: the react-router high/moderate advisories appearing in the same audit output are a separate finding requiring a react-router-dom bump to >=7.15.0.)

Guard on the exact TRMNL ingest shape before overriding, and validate the resulting Timestamp. Replace lines 162-172 with:

try {
  const parsedMessage = JSON.parse(newLoveMessage);
  if (
    parsedMessage &&
    typeof parsedMessage === 'object' &&
    typeof parsedMessage.text === 'string' &&
    typeof parsedMessage.timestamp === 'number' &&
    Number.isFinite(parsedMessage.timestamp)
  ) {
    messageData = {
      message: parsedMessage.text,
      timestamp: new Timestamp(
        Math.floor(parsedMessage.timestamp / 1000),
        (parsedMessage.timestamp % 1000) * 1_000_000  // ms remainder -> nanoseconds
      ),
    };
  }
} catch {
  // Not JSON; keep the plain-string messageData.
}

Note two bugs beyond the shape guard: (1) the original `parsedMessage.timestamp % 1000` is passed as nanoseconds but is actually a millisecond remainder, so even valid TRMNL input produces a slightly wrong sub-second component — it should be `* 1_000_000` to convert ms to ns, and seconds should be floored. (2) Anything that JSON-parses to a non-conforming object still falls through to the plain-string path with this guard, eliminating the NaN/undefined corruption.

Insert right after line 99, replacing the existing `if (!text)` block (functions/src/index.ts:95-99) with explicit type + length validation:

if (typeof text !== 'string' || text.length === 0) {
  console.warn('Missing or invalid text parameter');
  res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid text parameter' });
  return;
}
if (text.length > 5000) {
  console.warn('Text too long', { textLength: text.length });
  res.status(413).json({ error: 'Text too long (max 5000 characters)' });
  return;
}

This also eliminates the unhandled-shape crash (number/object inputs no longer reach text.length/text.substring at line 101). The 5000-char cap matches the verified client behavior (short transcript segments). Use 413 for the length case to distinguish it from the malformed-input 400 if desired; a single 400 is also acceptable.
